    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "agents"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " array can safely include the agent(s) affected by the goal—an agent pursuing this goal will ignore itself in the array. Therefore, you can use a single goal created with this method to cause an entire group of agents to mutually stay near one another."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Changing the "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "maxDistance"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " parameter determines how close to one another agents need to be in order for them to form a group. Changing the "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "maxAngle"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " parameter determines how tightly an agent will turn to maintain cohesion in the group."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You can combine separation, alignment, and cohesion goals to produce “flocking” behaviors in which a group of agents move together."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
